      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Property During Separation or Divorce in Queensland
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The property sale is often the largest single transaction in a separation. Here is how it works, what your rights are, and what to expect from the process.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Separation is one of the most common triggers for a property sale in Australia, and it is one of the most emotionally and legally complex situations an agent and vendor encounter. The property sale often happens in the middle of the most difficult period in two people's lives — while legal proceedings are active, while emotions are raw, and while both parties are trying to establish independent financial footing. This article explains the practical process of selling a jointly owned property during separation in Queensland, and what to expect from each stage.</p>

      <p>This is not legal or financial advice. If you are in the process of a separation or divorce and jointly own property, engage a family law solicitor before making any decisions about the property sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Legal authority to sell</h2>
      <p>For most jointly owned residential properties, both parties must agree to the sale and both must sign the agency agreement and the contract of sale. If both parties agree on selling — even if they disagree on almost everything else — the sale process can proceed relatively normally, with the proceeds held in trust by the conveyancing solicitor and distributed in accordance with either an agreed split or a court order.</p>

      <p>If one party refuses to sell, the other party cannot force a sale without a court order. For married couples, either party can apply to the Family Court of Australia for orders relating to the property, including an order requiring the sale. The Family Court has broad powers to make orders that are just and equitable based on the contributions and needs of each party. The process takes time and legal costs accumulate — most disputes that reach the court are resolved through negotiation before a hearing, but it can take months or years.</p>

      <p>For de facto couples (unmarried partners who lived together in a genuine domestic relationship for at least two years, or who have a child together), similar rights exist under the Family Law Act. The time limit for property settlement applications for de facto couples is two years from the date of separation. Missing this deadline can be costly — seek legal advice early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the property is valued in a settlement</h2>
      <p>Before a property settlement can be finalised — whether by agreement or court order — both parties need a reliable current market value for the property. This is typically established through a formal valuation from a licensed valuer, or through an agreed real estate appraisal. The value becomes the foundation for calculating each party's share of the property pool and is a critical input into any settlement negotiations.</p>

      <p>In practice, parties sometimes obtain separate appraisals that produce different values — and use those differences as negotiating leverage. An independent formal valuation, agreed to by both parties, is generally more reliable and reduces the risk of disputes about the starting point. Your family law solicitor will advise on the most appropriate approach for your situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agreeing on the agent</h2>
      <p>Both parties need to agree on which agent to appoint. This is sometimes the first test of whether a cooperative sale process is possible. The most practical approach is for both parties (or their solicitors) to agree on a shortlist of reputable agents in the area, interview them together or separately, and make a joint decision. An agent who is a personal friend or family connection to one party should be avoided, as it creates a perception of bias that can complicate an already difficult process.</p>

      <p>A good agent for a separation sale is one who communicates with both parties professionally and without taking sides, provides written updates that can be shared with both parties and their solicitors, manages the open home and buyer feedback process neutrally, and does not use knowledge of the vendor's circumstances to reduce their expectations.</p>

      <p>The agency agreement should be signed by both parties. If one party is unable or unwilling to sign, your solicitor should be involved before proceeding.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">During the campaign</h2>
      <p>Once the campaign is underway, practical questions arise: who is living in the property, how access for opens is managed, and how decisions about offers are made. These need to be agreed before the campaign starts rather than negotiated in the moment.</p>

      <p>If one party is still living in the property, they need to agree to present it appropriately for open homes and allow buyer access. If neither party is living in the property, it is vacant and typically easier to manage from a presentation standpoint.</p>

      <p>Decisions about price reductions, offers, and sale method require agreement from both parties. This can be a source of delay if communication between the parties has broken down. Having a clear communication protocol — for example, all correspondence to go through solicitors, or both parties agreeing to respond to offers within 48 hours — can reduce friction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement proceeds and distribution</h2>
      <p>The proceeds of the sale are typically held by the conveyancing solicitor in trust pending final distribution. Distribution is governed by either a binding financial agreement (a private agreement between the parties, formalised by solicitors) or a court consent order. In most cases, the net proceeds are split according to the agreed or ordered division, with any outstanding mortgage discharged at settlement and the residual divided.</p>

      <p>If there is an outstanding dispute about the distribution when settlement approaches, the proceeds can be held in a solicitor's trust account pending resolution. Settlement does not need to be held up by an unresolved financial dispute — the dispute can continue after settlement with the funds secured.</p>

